  - verses:
    - name: '1: Cyrus Allows the Exiles to Return'
      title: Cyrus Allows the Exiles to Return
      number: 1
      content: '  In the first year of King Cyrus of Persia,[[COMMENT(0)]] the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        fulfilled the prophecy he had given through Jeremiah.[[COMMENT(1)]] He stirred
        the heart of Cyrus to put this proclamation in writing and to send it throughout
        his kingdom:  '
      comments:
      - number: '1:1a '
        content: "The first year of Cyrus\u2019s reign over Babylon was 538 <span
          class=\"ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da\">b.c.</span>"
      - number: '1:1b '
        content: See Jer 25:11-12; 29:10.
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CThis is what King Cyrus of Persia says:\u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of heaven, has given me all the kingdoms of the earth. He has appointed
        me to build him a Temple at Jerusalem, which is in Judah. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Any of you who are his people may go to Jerusalem in Judah to rebuild
        this Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel, who lives
        in Jerusalem. And may your God be with you! '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Wherever this Jewish remnant is found, let their neighbors contribute
        toward their expenses by giving them silver and gold, supplies for the journey,
        and livestock, as well as a voluntary offering for the Temple of God in Jerusalem.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Then God stirred the hearts of the priests and Levites and the leaders
        of the tribes of Judah and Benjamin to go to Jerusalem to rebuild the Temple
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'And all their neighbors assisted by giving them articles of silver
        and gold, supplies for the journey, and livestock. They gave them many valuable
        gifts in addition to all the voluntary offerings.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "King Cyrus himself brought out the articles that King Nebuchadnezzar
        had taken from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple in Jerusalem
        and had placed in the temple of his own gods. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Cyrus directed Mithredath, the treasurer of Persia, to count these
        items and present them to Sheshbazzar, the leader of the exiles returning
        to Judah.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '1:8 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Sheshbazzar, the prince of Judah.</b>
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: This is a list of the items that were returned:gold basins30silver
        basins1,000silver incense burners[[COMMENT(0)]]29
      comments:
      - number: '1:9 '
        content: The meaning of this Hebrew word is uncertain.
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'gold bowls30silver bowls410other items1,000      '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: In all, there were 5,400 articles of gold and silver. Sheshbazzar
        brought all of these along when the exiles went from Babylon to Jerusalem.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Exiles Who Returned with Zerubbabel'
      title: Exiles Who Returned with Zerubbabel
      number: 1
      content: '  Here is the list of the Jewish exiles of the provinces who returned
        from their captivity. King Nebuchadnezzar had deported them to Babylon, but
        now they returned to Jerusalem and the other towns in Judah where they originally
        lived. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Their leaders were Zerubbabel, Jeshua, Nehemiah, Seraiah, Reelaiah,
        Mordecai, Bilshan, Mispar, Bigvai, Rehum, and Baanah.This is the number of
        the men of Israel who returned from exile:'
      comments: []
