      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: These are the Levites who returned from exile:The families of Jeshua
        and Kadmiel (descendants of Hodaviah)74
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: The singers of the family of Asaph128
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: 'The gatekeepers of the families of Shallum, Ater, Talmon, Akkub,
        Hatita, and Shobai139      '
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: 'The descendants of the following Temple servants returned from exile:Ziha,
        Hasupha, Tabbaoth,  '
      comments: []
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: 'Keros, Siaha, Padon,  '
      comments: []
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: 'Lebanah, Hagabah, Akkub,  '
      comments: []
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: 'Hagab, Shalmai,[[COMMENT(0)]] Hanan,  '
      comments:
      - number: '2:46 '
        content: As in an alternate reading of the Masoretic Text (see also Neh 7:48);
          the other alternate reads <b>Shamlai.</b>
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: 'Giddel, Gahar, Reaiah,  '
      comments: []
    - name: '48: '
      title: 
      number: 48
      content: 'Rezin, Nekoda, Gazzam,  '
      comments: []
    - name: '49: '
      title: 
      number: 49
      content: 'Uzza, Paseah, Besai,  '
      comments: []
    - name: '50: '
      title: 
      number: 50
      content: 'Asnah, Meunim, Nephusim,  '
      comments: []
    - name: '51: '
      title: 
      number: 51
      content: 'Bakbuk, Hakupha, Harhur,  '
      comments: []
    - name: '52: '
      title: 
      number: 52
      content: 'Bazluth, Mehida, Harsha,  '
      comments: []
    - name: '53: '
      title: 
      number: 53
      content: 'Barkos, Sisera, Temah,  '
      comments: []
    - name: '54: '
      title: 
      number: 54
      content: 'Neziah, and Hatipha.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '55: '
      title: 
      number: 55
      content: 'The descendants of these servants of King Solomon returned from exile:Sotai,
        Hassophereth, Peruda,  '
      comments: []
    - name: '56: '
      title: 
      number: 56
      content: 'Jaalah, Darkon, Giddel,  '
      comments: []
    - name: '57: '
      title: 
      number: 57
      content: 'Shephatiah, Hattil, Pokereth-hazzebaim, and Ami.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '58: '
      title: 
      number: 58
      content: "In all, the Temple servants and the descendants of Solomon\u2019s
        servants numbered 392.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '59: '
      title: 
      number: 59
      content: 'Another group returned at this time from the towns of Tel-melah,
        Tel-harsha, Kerub, Addan, and Immer. However, they could not prove that they
        or their families were descendants of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '60: '
      title: 
      number: 60
      content: "This group included the families of Delaiah, Tobiah, and Nekoda\u2014a
        total of 652 people.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '61: '
      title: 
      number: 61
      content: "Three families of priests\u2014Hobaiah, Hakkoz, and Barzillai\u2014also
        returned. (This Barzillai had married a woman who was a descendant of Barzillai
        of Gilead, and he had taken her family name.) "
      comments: []
    - name: '62: '
      title: 
      number: 62
      content: 'They searched for their names in the genealogical records, but they
        were not found, so they were disqualified from serving as priests. '
      comments: []
    - name: '63: '
      title: 
      number: 63
      content: "The governor told them not to eat the priests\u2019 share of food
        from the sacrifices until a priest could consult the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        about the matter by using the Urim and Thummim\u2014the sacred lots.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '64: '
      title: 
      number: 64
      content: 'So a total of 42,360 people returned to Judah, '
      comments: []
    - name: '65: '
      title: 
      number: 65
      content: 'in addition to 7,337 servants and 200 singers, both men and women. '
      comments: []
    - name: '66: '
      title: 
      number: 66
      content: 'They took with them 736 horses, 245 mules, '
      comments: []
    - name: '67: '
      title: 
      number: 67
      content: '435 camels, and 6,720 donkeys.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '68: '
      title: 
      number: 68
      content: "When they arrived at the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        in Jerusalem, some of the family leaders made voluntary offerings toward
        the rebuilding of God\u2019s Temple on its original site, "
      comments: []
    - name: '69: '
      title: 
      number: 69
      content: 'and each leader gave as much as he could. The total of their gifts
        came to 61,000 gold coins,[[COMMENT(0)]] 6,250 pounds[[COMMENT(1)]] of silver,
        and 100 robes for the priests.  '
      comments:
      - number: '2:69a '
        content: Hebrew <b>61,000 darics of gold, </b>about 1,100 pounds or 500 kilograms
          in weight.
      - number: '2:69b '
        content: Hebrew <b>5,000 minas </b>[3,000 kilograms].
    - name: '70: '
      title: 
      number: 70
      content: So the priests, the Levites, the singers, the gatekeepers, the Temple
        servants, and some of the common people settled in villages near Jerusalem.
        The rest of the people returned to their own towns throughout Israel.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Altar Is Rebuilt'
      title: The Altar Is Rebuilt
      number: 1
      content: '  In early autumn,[[COMMENT(0)]] when the Israelites had settled
        in their towns, all the people assembled in Jerusalem with a unified purpose. '
      comments:
      - number: '3:1 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>In the seventh month. </b>The year is not specified,
          so it may have been during Cyrus\u2019s first year (538 <span class=\"ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da\">b.c.</span>)
          or second year (537 <span class=\"ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da\">b.c.</span>).
          The seventh month of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar occurred within
          the months of September/October 538 <span class=\"ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da\">b.c.</span>
          and October/November 537 <span class=\"ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da\">b.c.</span>"
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Then Jeshua son of Jehozadak[[COMMENT(0)]] joined his fellow priests
        and Zerubbabel son of Shealtiel with his family in rebuilding the altar of
        the God of Israel. They wanted to sacrifice burnt offerings on it, as instructed
        in the Law of Moses, the man of God. '
      comments:
      - number: '3:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Jozadak, </b>a variant spelling of Jehozadak; also in
          3:8.
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Even though the people were afraid of the local residents, they rebuilt
        the altar at its old site. Then they began to sacrifice burnt offerings on
        the altar to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> each morning and evening.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'They celebrated the Festival of Shelters as prescribed in the Law,
        sacrificing the number of burnt offerings specified for each day of the festival. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'They also offered the regular burnt offerings and the offerings required
        for the new moon celebrations and the annual festivals as prescribed by the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. The people also gave voluntary offerings to
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: The People Begin to Rebuild the Temple'
      title: The People Begin to Rebuild the Temple
      number: 6
      content: "Fifteen days before the Festival of Shelters began,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        the priests had begun to sacrifice burnt offerings to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        This was even before they had started to lay the foundation of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple.  "
      comments:
      - number: '3:6 '
        content: Hebrew <b>On the first day of the seventh month. </b>This day in
          the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar occurred in September or October. The
          Festival of Shelters began on the fifteenth day of the seventh month.
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Then the people hired masons and carpenters and bought cedar logs
        from the people of Tyre and Sidon, paying them with food, wine, and olive
        oil. The logs were brought down from the Lebanon mountains and floated along
        the coast of the Mediterranean Sea[[COMMENT(0)]] to Joppa, for King Cyrus
        had given permission for this.  '
      comments:
      - number: '3:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the sea.</b>
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "The construction of the Temple of God began in midspring,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        during the second year after they arrived in Jerusalem. The work force was
        made up of everyone who had returned from exile, including Zerubbabel son
        of Shealtiel, Jeshua son of Jehozadak and his fellow priests, and all the
        Levites. The Levites who were twenty years old or older were put in charge
        of rebuilding the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple. "
      comments:
      - number: '3:8 '
        content: Hebrew <b>in the second month. </b>This month in the ancient Hebrew
          lunar calendar occurred within the months of April and May 536 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'The workers at the Temple of God were supervised by Jeshua with his
        sons and relatives, and Kadmiel and his sons, all descendants of Hodaviah.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        They were helped in this task by the Levites of the family of Henadad.  '
      comments:
      - number: '3:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>sons of Judah </b>(i.e., <b>bene Yehudah</b>). <b>Bene
          </b>might also be read here as the proper name Binnui; <b>Yehudah </b>is
          probably another name for Hodaviah. Compare 2:40; Neh 7:43; 1 Esdras 5:58.
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "When the builders completed the foundation of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        Temple, the priests put on their robes and took their places to blow their
        trumpets. And the Levites, descendants of Asaph, clashed their cymbals to
        praise the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, just as King David had prescribed. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "With praise and thanks, they sang this song to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:\u201CHe
        is so good!His faithful love for Israel endures forever!\u201DThen all the
        people gave a great shout, praising the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> because
        the foundation of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple had been
        laid.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "But many of the older priests, Levites, and other leaders who had
        seen the first Temple wept aloud when they saw the new Temple\u2019s foundation.
        The others, however, were shouting for joy. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: The joyful shouting and weeping mingled together in a loud noise that
        could be heard far in the distance.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Enemies Oppose the Rebuilding'
      title: Enemies Oppose the Rebuilding
      number: 1
      content: '  The enemies of Judah and Benjamin heard that the exiles were rebuilding
        a Temple to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "So they approached Zerubbabel and the other leaders and said, \u201CLet
        us build with you, for we worship your God just as you do. We have sacrificed
        to him ever since King Esarhaddon of Assyria brought us here.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "But Zerubbabel, Jeshua, and the other leaders of Israel replied,
        \u201CYou may have no part in this work. We alone will build the Temple for
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel, just as King Cyrus of
        Persia commanded us.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Then the local residents tried to discourage and frighten the people
        of Judah to keep them from their work. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: Later Opposition under Xerxes and Artaxerxes'
      title: Later Opposition under Xerxes and Artaxerxes
      number: 5
      content: 'They bribed agents to work against them and to frustrate their plans.
        This went on during the entire reign of King Cyrus of Persia and lasted until
        King Darius of Persia took the throne.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '4:5 '
        content: "Darius reigned 521\u2013486 <span class=\"ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da\">b.c.</span>"
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Years later when Xerxes[[COMMENT(0)]] began his reign, the enemies
        of Judah wrote a letter of accusation against the people of Judah and Jerusalem.  '
      comments:
      - number: '4:6 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>Ahasuerus, </b>another name for Xerxes. He reigned 486\u2013465
          <span class=\"ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da\">b.c.</span>"
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Even later, during the reign of King Artaxerxes of Persia,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        the enemies of Judah, led by Bishlam, Mithredath, and Tabeel, sent a letter
        to Artaxerxes in the Aramaic language, and it was translated for the king.  '
      comments:
      - number: '4:7 '
        content: "Artaxerxes reigned 465\u2013424 <span class=\"ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da\">b.c.</span>  "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: '  [[COMMENT(0)]]Rehum the governor and Shimshai the court secretary
        wrote the letter, telling King Artaxerxes about the situation in Jerusalem. '
      comments:
      - number: '4:8 '
        content: "  The original text of 4:8\u20136:18 is in Aramaic.  "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "They greeted the king for all their colleagues\u2014the judges and
        local leaders, the people of Tarpel, the Persians, the Babylonians, and the
        people of Erech and Susa (that is, Elam). "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'They also sent greetings from the rest of the people whom the great
        and noble Ashurbanipal[[COMMENT(0)]] had deported and relocated in Samaria
        and throughout the neighboring lands of the province west of the Euphrates
        River.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '4:10a '
        content: Aramaic <b>Osnappar, </b>another name for Ashurbanipal.
      - number: '4:10b '
        content: Aramaic <b>the province beyond the river; </b>also in 4:11, 16,
          17, 20.
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "This is a copy of their letter:\u201CTo King Artaxerxes, from your
        loyal subjects in the province west of the Euphrates River.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CThe king should know that the Jews who came here to Jerusalem
        from Babylon are rebuilding this rebellious and evil city. They have already
        laid the foundation and will soon finish its walls. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'And the king should know that if this city is rebuilt and its walls
        are completed, it will be much to your disadvantage, for the Jews will then
        refuse to pay their tribute, customs, and tolls to you.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "\u201CSince we are your loyal subjects[[COMMENT(0)]] and do not want
        to see the king dishonored in this way, we have sent the king this information. "
      comments:
      - number: '4:14 '
        content: Aramaic <b>Since we eat the salt of the palace.</b>
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "We suggest that a search be made in your ancestors\u2019 records,
        where you will discover what a rebellious city this has been in the past.
        In fact, it was destroyed because of its long and troublesome history of
        revolt against the kings and countries who controlled it. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "We declare to the king that if this city is rebuilt and its walls
        are completed, the province west of the Euphrates River will be lost to you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Then King Artaxerxes sent this reply:\u201CTo Rehum the governor,
        Shimshai the court secretary, and their colleagues living in Samaria and
        throughout the province west of the Euphrates River. Greetings.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CThe letter you sent has been translated and read to me. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'I ordered a search of the records and have found that Jerusalem has
        indeed been a hotbed of insurrection against many kings. In fact, rebellion
        and revolt are normal there! '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Powerful kings have ruled over Jerusalem and the entire province
        west of the Euphrates River, receiving tribute, customs, and tolls. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'Therefore, issue orders to have these men stop their work. That city
        must not be rebuilt except at my express command. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "Be diligent, and don\u2019t neglect this matter, for we must not
        permit the situation to harm the king\u2019s interests.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: The Rebuilding Resumes'
      title: The Rebuilding Resumes
      number: 23
      content: 'When this letter from King Artaxerxes was read to Rehum, Shimshai,
        and their colleagues, they hurried to Jerusalem. Then, with a show of strength,
        they forced the Jews to stop building.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: So the work on the Temple of God in Jerusalem had stopped, and it
        remained at a standstill until the second year of the reign of King Darius
        of Persia.[[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: '4:24 '
        content: "The second year of Darius\u2019s reign was 520 <span class=\"ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da\">b.c.</span>
          The narrative started in 4:1-5 is resumed at verse 24."
  - verses:
    - name: '1: '
      title: 
      number: 1
      content: '  At that time the prophets Haggai and Zechariah son of Iddo prophesied
        to the Jews in Judah and Jerusalem. They prophesied in the name of the God
        of Israel who was over them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Zerubbabel son of Shealtiel and Jeshua son of Jehozadak[[COMMENT(0)]]
        responded by starting again to rebuild the Temple of God in Jerusalem. And
        the prophets of God were with them and helped them.  '
      comments:
      - number: '5:2 '
        content: Aramaic <b>Jozadak, </b>a variant spelling of Jehozadak.
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "But Tattenai, governor of the province west of the Euphrates River,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and Shethar-bozenai and their colleagues soon arrived in Jerusalem and asked,
        \u201CWho gave you permission to rebuild this Temple and restore this structure?\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '5:3 '
        content: Aramaic <b>the province beyond the river; </b>also in 5:6.
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'They also asked for[[COMMENT(0)]] the names of all the men working
        on the Temple. '
      comments:
      - number: '5:4 '
        content: As in one Hebrew manuscript and Greek and Syriac versions; Masoretic
          Text reads <b>Then we told them.</b>
    - name: "5: Tattenai\u2019s Letter to King Darius"
      title: "Tattenai\u2019s Letter to King Darius"
      number: 5
      content: 'But because their God was watching over them, the leaders of the
        Jews were not prevented from building until a report was sent to Darius and
        he returned his decision.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'This is a copy of the letter that Tattenai the governor, Shethar-bozenai,
        and the other officials of the province west of the Euphrates River sent
        to King Darius:  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "\u201CTo King Darius. Greetings.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CThe king should know that we went to the construction site
        of the Temple of the great God in the province of Judah. It is being rebuilt
        with specially prepared stones, and timber is being laid in its walls. The
        work is going forward with great energy and success.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CWe asked the leaders, \u2018Who gave you permission to rebuild
        this Temple and restore this structure?\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'And we demanded their names so that we could tell you who the leaders
        were.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201CThis was their answer: \u2018We are the servants of the God
        of heaven and earth, and we are rebuilding the Temple that was built here
        many years ago by a great king of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'But because our ancestors angered the God of heaven, he abandoned
        them to King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon,[[COMMENT(0)]] who destroyed this
        Temple and exiled the people to Babylonia. '
      comments:
      - number: '5:12 '
        content: Aramaic <b>Nebuchadnezzar the Chaldean.</b>
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'However, King Cyrus of Babylon,[[COMMENT(0)]] during the first year
        of his reign, issued a decree that the Temple of God should be rebuilt. '
      comments:
      - number: '5:13 '
        content: King Cyrus of Persia is here identified as the king of Babylon because
          Persia had conquered the Babylonian Empire.
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'King Cyrus returned the gold and silver cups that Nebuchadnezzar
        had taken from the Temple of God in Jerusalem and had placed in the temple
        of Babylon. These cups were taken from that temple and presented to a man
        named Sheshbazzar, whom King Cyrus appointed as governor of Judah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'The king instructed him to return the cups to their place in Jerusalem
        and to rebuild the Temple of God there on its original site. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "So this Sheshbazzar came and laid the foundations of the Temple of
        God in Jerusalem. The people have been working on it ever since, though it
        is not yet completed.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u201CTherefore, if it pleases the king, we request that a search
        be made in the royal archives of Babylon to discover whether King Cyrus ever
        issued a decree to rebuild God\u2019s Temple in Jerusalem. And then let the
        king send us his decision in this matter.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Darius Approves the Rebuilding'
      title: Darius Approves the Rebuilding
      number: 1
      content: '  So King Darius issued orders that a search be made in the Babylonian
        archives, which were stored in the treasury. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "But it was at the fortress at Ecbatana in the province of Media that
        a scroll was found. This is what it said:\u201CMemorandum:  "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "\u201CIn the first year of King Cyrus\u2019s reign, a decree was
        sent out concerning the Temple of God at Jerusalem.\u201CLet the Temple be
        rebuilt on the site where Jews used to offer their sacrifices, using the
        original foundations. Its height will be ninety feet, and its width will
        be ninety feet.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '6:3 '
        content: "Aramaic <b>Its height will be 60 cubits </b>[27.6 meters], <b>and
          its width will be 60 cubits. </b>It is commonly held that this verse should
          be emended to read: \u201CIts height will be 30 cubits [45 feet or 13.8
          meters], its length will be 60 cubits [90 feet or 27.6 meters], and its
          width will be 20 cubits [30 feet or 9.2 meters]\u201D; compare 1 Kgs 6:2.
          The emendation regarding the width is supported by the Syriac version."
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Every three layers of specially prepared stones will be topped by
        a layer of timber. All expenses will be paid by the royal treasury. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Furthermore, the gold and silver cups, which were taken to Babylon
        by Nebuchadnezzar from the Temple of God in Jerusalem, must be returned to
        Jerusalem and put back where they belong. Let them be taken back to the Temple
        of God.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "So King Darius sent this message:\u201CNow therefore, Tattenai, governor
        of the province west of the Euphrates River,[[COMMENT(0)]] and Shethar-bozenai,
        and your colleagues and other officials west of the Euphrates River\u2014stay
        away from there! "
      comments:
      - number: '6:6 '
        content: Aramaic <b>the province beyond the river; </b>also in 6:6b, 8, 13.
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Do not disturb the construction of the Temple of God. Let it be rebuilt
        on its original site, and do not hinder the governor of Judah and the elders
        of the Jews in their work.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CMoreover, I hereby decree that you are to help these elders
        of the Jews as they rebuild this Temple of God. You must pay the full construction
        costs, without delay, from my taxes collected in the province west of the
        Euphrates River so that the work will not be interrupted.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CGive the priests in Jerusalem whatever is needed in the way
        of young bulls, rams, and male lambs for the burnt offerings presented to
        the God of heaven. And without fail, provide them with as much wheat, salt,
        wine, and olive oil as they need each day. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Then they will be able to offer acceptable sacrifices to the God
        of heaven and pray for the welfare of the king and his sons.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201CThose who violate this decree in any way will have a beam pulled
        from their house. Then they will be lifted up and impaled on it, and their
        house will be reduced to a pile of rubble.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '6:11 '
        content: Aramaic <b>a dunghill.</b>
    - name: "12: The Temple\u2019s Dedication"
      title: "The Temple\u2019s Dedication"
      number: 12
      content: "May the God who has chosen the city of Jerusalem as the place to
        honor his name destroy any king or nation that violates this command and
        destroys this Temple.\u201CI, Darius, have issued this decree. Let it be
        obeyed with all diligence.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Tattenai, governor of the province west of the Euphrates River, and
        Shethar-bozenai and their colleagues complied at once with the command of
        King Darius. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'So the Jewish elders continued their work, and they were greatly
        encouraged by the preaching of the prophets Haggai and Zechariah son of Iddo.
        The Temple was finally finished, as had been commanded by the God of Israel
        and decreed by Cyrus, Darius, and Artaxerxes, the kings of Persia. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "The Temple was completed on March 12,[[COMMENT(0)]] during the sixth
        year of King Darius\u2019s reign.  "
      comments:
      - number: '6:15 '
        content: Aramaic <b>on the third day of the month Adar, </b>of the ancient
          Hebrew lunar calendar. A number of events in Ezra can be cross-checked
          with dates in surviving Persian records and related accurately to our modern
          calendar. This day was March 12, 515 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'The Temple of God was then dedicated with great joy by the people
        of Israel, the priests, the Levites, and the rest of the people who had returned
        from exile. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'During the dedication ceremony for the Temple of God, 100 young bulls,
        200 rams, and 400 male lambs were sacrificed. And 12 male goats were presented
        as a sin offering for the twelve tribes of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: Celebration of Passover'
      title: Celebration of Passover
      number: 18
      content: 'Then the priests and Levites were divided into their various divisions
        to serve at the Temple of God in Jerusalem, as prescribed in the Book of
        Moses.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'On April 21[[COMMENT(0)]] the returned exiles celebrated Passover. '
      comments:
      - number: '6:19 '
        content: Hebrew <b>On the fourteenth day of the first month, </b>of the ancient
          Hebrew lunar calendar. This day was April 21, 515 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>;
          also see note on 6:15.
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'The priests and Levites had purified themselves and were ceremonially
        clean. So they slaughtered the Passover lamb for all the returned exiles,
        for their fellow priests, and for themselves. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'The Passover meal was eaten by the people of Israel who had returned
        from exile and by the others in the land who had turned from their corrupt
        practices to worship the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: Then they celebrated the Festival of Unleavened Bread for seven days.
        There was great joy throughout the land because the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had caused the king of Assyria[[COMMENT(0)]] to be favorable to them, so
        that he helped them to rebuild the Temple of God, the God of Israel.
      comments:
      - number: '6:22 '
        content: King Darius of Persia is here identified as the king of Assyria
          because Persia had conquered the Babylonian Empire, which included the
          earlier Assyrian Empire.
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Ezra Arrives in Jerusalem'
      title: Ezra Arrives in Jerusalem
      number: 1
      content: '  Many years later, during the reign of King Artaxerxes of Persia,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        there was a man named Ezra. He was the son[[COMMENT(1)]] of Seraiah, son
        of Azariah, son of Hilkiah, '
      comments:
      - number: '7:1a '
        content: "Artaxerxes reigned 465\u2013424 <span class=\"ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da\">b.c.</span>"
      - number: '7:1b '
        content: Or <b>descendant; </b>see 1 Chr 6:14.
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'son of Shallum, son of Zadok, son of Ahitub, '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'son of Amariah, son of Azariah, son[[COMMENT(0)]] of Meraioth, '
      comments:
      - number: '7:3 '
        content: Or <b>descendant; </b>see 1 Chr 6:6-10.
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'son of Zerahiah, son of Uzzi, son of Bukki, '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'son of Abishua, son of Phinehas, son of Eleazar, son of Aaron the
        high priest.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '7:5 '
        content: Or <b>the first priest.</b>
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'This Ezra was a scribe who was well versed in the Law of Moses, which
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel, had given to the people
        of Israel. He came up to Jerusalem from Babylon, and the king gave him everything
        he asked for, because the gracious hand of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        his God was on him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Some of the people of Israel, as well as some of the priests, Levites,
        singers, gatekeepers, and Temple servants, traveled up to Jerusalem with
        him in the seventh year of King Artaxerxes\u2019 reign.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Ezra arrived in Jerusalem in August[[COMMENT(0)]] of that year. '
      comments:
      - number: '7:8 '
        content: Hebrew <b>in the fifth month. </b>This month in the ancient Hebrew
          lunar calendar occurred within the months of August and September 458 <span
          class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'He had arranged to leave Babylon on April 8, the first day of the
        new year,[[COMMENT(0)]] and he arrived at Jerusalem on August 4,[[COMMENT(1)]]
        for the gracious hand of his God was on him. '
      comments:
      - number: '7:9a '
        content: Hebrew <b>on the first day of the first month, </b>of the ancient
          Hebrew lunar calendar. This day was April 8, 458 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>;
          also see note on 6:15.
      - number: '7:9b '
        content: 'Hebrew <b>on the first day of the fifth month, </b>of the ancient
          Hebrew lunar calendar. This day was August 4, 458 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>;
          also see note on 6:15.  '
    - name: "10: Artaxerxes\u2019 Letter to Ezra"
      title: "Artaxerxes\u2019 Letter to Ezra"
      number: 10
      content: 'This was because Ezra had determined to study and obey the Law of
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and to teach those decrees and regulations
        to the people of Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'King Artaxerxes had given a copy of the following letter to Ezra,
        the priest and scribe who studied and taught the commands and decrees of
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> to Israel:  '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "  [[COMMENT(0)]]\u201CFrom Artaxerxes, the king of kings, to Ezra
        the priest, the teacher of the law of the God of heaven. Greetings.  "
      comments:
      - number: '7:12 '
        content: '  The original text of 7:12-26 is in Aramaic.  '
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CI decree that any of the people of Israel in my kingdom, including
        the priests and Levites, may volunteer to return to Jerusalem with you. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "I and my council of seven hereby instruct you to conduct an inquiry
        into the situation in Judah and Jerusalem, based on your God\u2019s law,
        which is in your hand. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'We also commission you to take with you silver and gold, which we
        are freely presenting as an offering to the God of Israel who lives in Jerusalem.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "\u201CFurthermore, you are to take any silver and gold that you may
        obtain from the province of Babylon, as well as the voluntary offerings of
        the people and the priests that are presented for the Temple of their God
        in Jerusalem. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'These donations are to be used specifically for the purchase of bulls,
        rams, male lambs, and the appropriate grain offerings and liquid offerings,
        all of which will be offered on the altar of the Temple of your God in Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Any silver and gold that is left over may be used in whatever way
        you and your colleagues feel is the will of your God.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "\u201CBut as for the cups we are entrusting to you for the service
        of the Temple of your God, deliver them all to the God of Jerusalem. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "If you need anything else for your God\u2019s Temple or for any similar
        needs, you may take it from the royal treasury.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CI, Artaxerxes the king, hereby send this decree to all the
        treasurers in the province west of the Euphrates River[[COMMENT(0)]]: \u2018You
        are to give Ezra, the priest and teacher of the law of the God of heaven,
        whatever he requests of you. "
      comments:
      - number: '7:21 '
        content: Aramaic <b>the province beyond the river; </b>also in 7:25.
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'You are to give him up to 7,500 pounds[[COMMENT(0)]] of silver, 500
        bushels[[COMMENT(1)]] of wheat, 550 gallons of wine, 550 gallons of olive
        oil,[[COMMENT(2)]] and an unlimited supply of salt. '
      comments:
      - number: '7:22a '
        content: Aramaic <b>100 talents </b>[3,400 kilograms].
      - number: '7:22b '
        content: Aramaic <b>100 cors </b>[22 kiloliters].
      - number: '7:22c '
        content: Aramaic <b>100 baths </b>[2.1 kiloliters] <b>of wine, 100 baths
          of olive oil.</b>
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Be careful to provide whatever the God of heaven demands for his
        Temple, for why should we risk bringing God\u2019s anger against the realm
        of the king and his sons? "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "I also decree that no priest, Levite, singer, gatekeeper, Temple
        servant, or other worker in this Temple of God will be required to pay tribute,
        customs, or tolls of any kind.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "\u201CAnd you, Ezra, are to use the wisdom your God has given you
        to appoint magistrates and judges who know your God\u2019s laws to govern
        all the people in the province west of the Euphrates River. Teach the law
        to anyone who does not know it. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: Ezra Praises the '
      title: 'Ezra Praises the '
      number: 26
      content: "Anyone who refuses to obey the law of your God and the law of the
        king will be punished immediately, either by death, banishment, confiscation
        of goods, or imprisonment.\u201D<smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>  "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'Praise the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of our ancestors,
        who made the king want to beautify the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        in Jerusalem! '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: And praise him for demonstrating such unfailing love to me by honoring
        me before the king, his council, and all his mighty nobles! I felt encouraged
        because the gracious hand of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> my God was on
        me. And I gathered some of the leaders of Israel to return with me to Jerusalem.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Exiles Who Returned with Ezra'
      title: Exiles Who Returned with Ezra
      number: 1
      content: '  Here is a list of the family leaders and the genealogies of those
        who came with me from Babylon during the reign of King Artaxerxes:  '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'From the family of Phinehas: Gershom.From the family of Ithamar:
        Daniel.From the family of David: Hattush, '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'a descendant of Shecaniah.From the family of Parosh: Zechariah and
        150 other men were registered.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'From the family of Pahath-moab: Eliehoenai son of Zerahiah and 200
        other men.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'From the family of Zattu[[COMMENT(0)]]: Shecaniah son of Jahaziel
        and 300 other men.  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:5 '
        content: As in some Greek manuscripts (see also 1 Esdras 8:32); Hebrew lacks
          <b>Zattu.</b>
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'From the family of Adin: Ebed son of Jonathan and 50 other men.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'From the family of Elam: Jeshaiah son of Athaliah and 70 other men.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'From the family of Shephatiah: Zebadiah son of Michael and 80 other
        men.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'From the family of Joab: Obadiah son of Jehiel and 218 other men.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'From the family of Bani[[COMMENT(0)]]: Shelomith son of Josiphiah
        and 160 other men.  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:10 '
        content: As in some Greek manuscripts (see also 1 Esdras 8:36); Hebrew lacks
          <b>Bani.</b>
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'From the family of Bebai: Zechariah son of Bebai and 28 other men.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'From the family of Azgad: Johanan son of Hakkatan and 110 other men.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'From the family of Adonikam, who came later[[COMMENT(0)]]: Eliphelet,
        Jeuel, Shemaiah, and 60 other men.  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:13 '
        content: Or <b>who were the last of his family.</b>
    - name: "14: Ezra\u2019s Journey to Jerusalem"
      title: "Ezra\u2019s Journey to Jerusalem"
      number: 14
      content: 'From the family of Bigvai: Uthai, Zaccur,[[COMMENT(0)]] and 70 other
        men.  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:14 '
        content: As in Greek and Syriac versions and an alternate reading of the
          Masoretic Text; the other alternate reads <b>Zabbud.</b>
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'I assembled the exiles at the Ahava Canal, and we camped there for
        three days while I went over the lists of the people and the priests who
        had arrived. I found that not one Levite had volunteered to come along. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'So I sent for Eliezer, Ariel, Shemaiah, Elnathan, Jarib, Elnathan,
        Nathan, Zechariah, and Meshullam, who were leaders of the people. I also
        sent for Joiarib and Elnathan, who were men of discernment. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'I sent them to Iddo, the leader of the Levites at Casiphia, to ask
        him and his relatives and the Temple servants to send us ministers for the
        Temple of God at Jerusalem.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Since the gracious hand of our God was on us, they sent us a man
        named Sherebiah, along with eighteen of his sons and brothers. He was a very
        astute man and a descendant of Mahli, who was a descendant of Levi son of
        Israel.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:18 '
        content: <b>Israel </b>is the name that God gave to Jacob.
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'They also sent Hashabiah, together with Jeshaiah from the descendants
        of Merari, and twenty of his sons and brothers, '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "and 220 Temple servants. The Temple servants were assistants to the
        Levites\u2014a group of Temple workers first instituted by King David and
        his officials. They were all listed by name.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'And there by the Ahava Canal, I gave orders for all of us to fast
        and humble ourselves before our God. We prayed that he would give us a safe
        journey and protect us, our children, and our goods as we traveled. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "For I was ashamed to ask the king for soldiers and horsemen[[COMMENT(0)]]
        to accompany us and protect us from enemies along the way. After all, we
        had told the king, \u201COur God\u2019s hand of protection is on all who
        worship him, but his fierce anger rages against those who abandon him.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '8:22 '
        content: Or <b>charioteers.</b>
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'So we fasted and earnestly prayed that our God would take care of
        us, and he heard our prayer.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "I appointed twelve leaders of the priests\u2014Sherebiah, Hashabiah,
        and ten other priests\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'to be in charge of transporting the silver, the gold, the gold bowls,
        and the other items that the king, his council, his officials, and all the
        people of Israel had presented for the Temple of God. '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'I weighed the treasure as I gave it to them and found the totals
        to be as follows:24 tons[[COMMENT(0)]] of silver,7,500 pounds[[COMMENT(1)]]
        of silver articles,7,500 pounds of gold,  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:26a '
        content: Hebrew <b>650 talents </b>[22 metric tons].
      - number: '8:26b '
        content: Hebrew <b>100 talents </b>[3,400 kilograms]; also in 8:26c.
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: '20 gold bowls, equal in value to 1,000 gold coins,[[COMMENT(0)]]2
        fine articles of polished bronze, as precious as gold.  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:27 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1,000 darics, </b>about 19 pounds or 8.6 kilograms in
          weight.
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "And I said to these priests, \u201CYou and these treasures have been
        set apart as holy to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. This silver and gold
        is a voluntary offering to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of our
        ancestors. "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "Guard these treasures well until you present them to the leading
        priests, the Levites, and the leaders of Israel, who will weigh them at the
        storerooms of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Temple in Jerusalem.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'So the priests and the Levites accepted the task of transporting
        these treasures of silver and gold to the Temple of our God in Jerusalem.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'We broke camp at the Ahava Canal on April 19[[COMMENT(0)]] and started
        off to Jerusalem. And the gracious hand of our God protected us and saved
        us from enemies and bandits along the way. '
      comments:
      - number: '8:31 '
        content: Hebrew <b>on the twelfth day of the first month, </b>of the ancient
          Hebrew lunar calendar. This day was April 19, 458 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>;
          also see note on 6:15.
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'So we arrived safely in Jerusalem, where we rested for three days.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "On the fourth day after our arrival, the silver, gold, and other
        valuables were weighed at the Temple of our God and entrusted to Meremoth
        son of Uriah the priest and to Eleazar son of Phinehas, along with Jozabad
        son of Jeshua and Noadiah son of Binnui\u2014both of whom were Levites. "
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: 'Everything was accounted for by number and weight, and the total
        weight was officially recorded.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'Then the exiles who had come out of captivity sacrificed burnt offerings
        to the God of Israel. They presented twelve bulls for all the people of Israel,
        as well as ninety-six rams and seventy-seven male lambs. They also offered
        twelve male goats as a sin offering. All this was given as a burnt offering
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "The king\u2019s decrees were delivered to his highest officers and
        the governors of the province west of the Euphrates River,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        who then cooperated by supporting the people and the Temple of God."
      comments:
      - number: '8:36 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the province beyond the river.</b>
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Ezra\u2019s Prayer concerning Intermarriage"
      title: "Ezra\u2019s Prayer concerning Intermarriage"
      number: 1
      content: "  When these things had been done, the Jewish leaders came to me
        and said, \u201CMany of the people of Israel, and even some of the priests
        and Levites, have not kept themselves separate from the other peoples living
        in the land. They have taken up the detestable practices of the Canaanites,
        Hittites, Perizzites, Jebusites, Ammonites, Moabites, Egyptians, and Amorites. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "For the men of Israel have married women from these people and have
        taken them as wives for their sons. So the holy race has become polluted
        by these mixed marriages. Worse yet, the leaders and officials have led the
        way in this outrage.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'When I heard this, I tore my cloak and my shirt, pulled hair from
        my head and beard, and sat down utterly shocked. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'Then all who trembled at the words of the God of Israel came and
        sat with me because of this outrage committed by the returned exiles. And
        I sat there utterly appalled until the time of the evening sacrifice.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'At the time of the sacrifice, I stood up from where I had sat in
        mourning with my clothes torn. I fell to my knees and lifted my hands to
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> my God. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "I prayed,\u201CO my God, I am utterly ashamed; I blush to lift up
        my face to you. For our sins are piled higher than our heads, and our guilt
        has reached to the heavens. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'From the days of our ancestors until now, we have been steeped in
        sin. That is why we and our kings and our priests have been at the mercy
        of the pagan kings of the land. We have been killed, captured, robbed, and
        disgraced, just as we are today.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CBut now we have been given a brief moment of grace, for the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our God has allowed a few of us to survive as
        a remnant. He has given us security in this holy place. Our God has brightened
        our eyes and granted us some relief from our slavery. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'For we were slaves, but in his unfailing love our God did not abandon
        us in our slavery. Instead, he caused the kings of Persia to treat us favorably.
        He revived us so we could rebuild the Temple of our God and repair its ruins.
        He has given us a protective wall in Judah and Jerusalem.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201CAnd now, O our God, what can we say after all of this? For
        once again we have abandoned your commands! "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Your servants the prophets warned us when they said, \u2018The land
        you are entering to possess is totally defiled by the detestable practices
        of the people living there. From one end to the other, the land is filled
        with corruption. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Don\u2019t let your daughters marry their sons! Don\u2019t take their
        daughters as wives for your sons. Don\u2019t ever promote the peace and prosperity
        of those nations. If you follow these instructions, you will be strong and
        will enjoy the good things the land produces, and you will leave this prosperity
        to your children forever.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CNow we are being punished because of our wickedness and our
        great guilt. But we have actually been punished far less than we deserve,
        for you, our God, have allowed some of us to survive as a remnant. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "But even so, we are again breaking your commands and intermarrying
        with people who do these detestable things. Won\u2019t your anger be enough
        to destroy us, so that even this little remnant no longer survives? "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, God of Israel, you are just. We come
        before you in our guilt as nothing but an escaped remnant, though in such
        a condition none of us can stand in your presence.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The People Confess Their Sin'
      title: The People Confess Their Sin
      number: 1
      content: "  While Ezra prayed and made this confession, weeping and lying face
        down on the ground in front of the Temple of God, a very large crowd of people
        from Israel\u2014men, women, and children\u2014gathered and wept bitterly
        with him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Then Shecaniah son of Jehiel, a descendant of Elam, said to Ezra,
        \u201CWe have been unfaithful to our God, for we have married these pagan
        women of the land. But in spite of this there is hope for Israel. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Let us now make a covenant with our God to divorce our pagan wives
        and to send them away with their children. We will follow the advice given
        by you and by the others who respect the commands of our God. Let it be done
        according to the Law of God. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Get up, for it is your duty to tell us how to proceed in setting
        things straight. We are behind you, so be strong and take action.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'So Ezra stood up and demanded that the leaders of the priests and
        the Levites and all the people of Israel swear that they would do as Shecaniah
        had said. And they all swore a solemn oath. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Then Ezra left the front of the Temple of God and went to the room
        of Jehohanan son of Eliashib. He spent the night[[COMMENT(0)]] there without
        eating or drinking anything. He was still in mourning because of the unfaithfulness
        of the returned exiles.  '
      comments:
      - number: '10:6 '
        content: As in parallel text at 1 Esdras 9:2; Hebrew reads <b>He went.</b>
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Then a proclamation was made throughout Judah and Jerusalem that
        all the exiles should come to Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Those who failed to come within three days would, if the leaders
        and elders so decided, forfeit all their property and be expelled from the
        assembly of the exiles.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Within three days, all the people of Judah and Benjamin had gathered
        in Jerusalem. This took place on December 19,[[COMMENT(0)]] and all the people
        were sitting in the square before the Temple of God. They were trembling
        both because of the seriousness of the matter and because it was raining. '
      comments:
      - number: '10:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>on the twentieth day of the ninth month, </b>of the ancient
          Hebrew lunar calendar. This day was December 19, 458 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>;
          also see note on 6:15.
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Then Ezra the priest stood and said to them: \u201CYou have committed
        a terrible sin. By marrying pagan women, you have increased Israel\u2019s
        guilt. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "So now confess your sin to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God
        of your ancestors, and do what he demands. Separate yourselves from the people
        of the land and from these pagan women.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Then the whole assembly raised their voices and answered, \u201CYes,
        you are right; we must do as you say!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Then they added, \u201CThis isn\u2019t something that can be done
        in a day or two, for many of us are involved in this extremely sinful affair.
        And this is the rainy season, so we cannot stay out here much longer. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Let our leaders act on behalf of us all. Let everyone who has a pagan
        wife come at a scheduled time, accompanied by the leaders and judges of his
        city, so that the fierce anger of our God concerning this affair may be turned
        away from us.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Only Jonathan son of Asahel and Jahzeiah son of Tikvah opposed this
        course of action, and they were supported by Meshullam and Shabbethai the
        Levite.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'So this was the plan they followed. Ezra selected leaders to represent
        their families, designating each of the representatives by name. On December
        29,[[COMMENT(0)]] the leaders sat down to investigate the matter. '
      comments:
      - number: '10:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>On the first day of the tenth month, </b>of the ancient
          Hebrew lunar calendar. This day was December 29, 458 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>;
          also see note on 6:15.
    - name: '17: Those Guilty of Intermarriage'
      title: Those Guilty of Intermarriage
      number: 17
      content: 'By March 27, the first day of the new year,[[COMMENT(0)]] they had
        finished dealing with all the men who had married pagan wives.  '
      comments:
      - number: '10:17 '
        content: Hebrew <b>By the first day of the first month, </b>of the ancient
          Hebrew lunar calendar. This day was March 27, 457 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>;
          also see note on 6:15.
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'These are the priests who had married pagan wives:From the family
        of Jeshua son of Jehozadak[[COMMENT(0)]] and his brothers: Maaseiah, Eliezer,
        Jarib, and Gedaliah. '
      comments:
      - number: '10:18 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Jozadak, </b>a variant spelling of Jehozadak.
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'They vowed to divorce their wives, and they each acknowledged their
        guilt by offering a ram as a guilt offering.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'From the family of Immer: Hanani and Zebadiah.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'From the family of Harim: Maaseiah, Elijah, Shemaiah, Jehiel, and
        Uzziah.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'From the family of Pashhur: Elioenai, Maaseiah, Ishmael, Nethanel,
        Jozabad, and Elasah.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'These are the Levites who were guilty: Jozabad, Shimei, Kelaiah (also
        called Kelita), Pethahiah, Judah, and Eliezer.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'This is the singer who was guilty: Eliashib.These are the gatekeepers
        who were guilty: Shallum, Telem, and Uri.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'These are the other people of Israel who were guilty:From the family
        of Parosh: Ramiah, Izziah, Malkijah, Mijamin, Eleazar, Hashabiah,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and Benaiah.  '
      comments:
      - number: '10:25 '
        content: As in parallel text at 1 Esdras 9:26; Hebrew reads <b>Malkijah.</b>
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'From the family of Elam: Mattaniah, Zechariah, Jehiel, Abdi, Jeremoth,
        and Elijah.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: 'From the family of Zattu: Elioenai, Eliashib, Mattaniah, Jeremoth,
        Zabad, and Aziza.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'From the family of Bebai: Jehohanan, Hananiah, Zabbai, and Athlai.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'From the family of Bani: Meshullam, Malluch, Adaiah, Jashub, Sheal,
        and Jeremoth.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'From the family of Pahath-moab: Adna, Kelal, Benaiah, Maaseiah, Mattaniah,
        Bezalel, Binnui, and Manasseh.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: 'From the family of Harim: Eliezer, Ishijah, Malkijah, Shemaiah, Shimeon, '
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'Benjamin, Malluch, and Shemariah.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'From the family of Hashum: Mattenai, Mattattah, Zabad, Eliphelet,
        Jeremai, Manasseh, and Shimei.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: 'From the family of Bani: Maadai, Amram, Uel, '
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'Benaiah, Bedeiah, Keluhi, '
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: 'Vaniah, Meremoth, Eliashib, '
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: 'Mattaniah, Mattenai, and Jaasu.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: 'From the family of Binnui[[COMMENT(0)]]: Shimei, '
      comments:
      - number: '10:37-38 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>Jaasu, </b><b>Bani, Binnui.</b>
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: 'Shelemiah, Nathan, Adaiah, '
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: 'Macnadebai, Shashai, Sharai, '
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: 'Azarel, Shelemiah, Shemariah, '
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: 'Shallum, Amariah, and Joseph.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: 'From the family of Nebo: Jeiel, Mattithiah, Zabad, Zebina, Jaddai,
        Joel, and Benaiah.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: Each of these men had a pagan wife, and some even had children by
        these wives.[[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
